node.text:
Well.. I’m a woman of my word. 
3 likes = Tree climb. 
I understand there is a lot of stress and uneasiness in regards to current events. My contributions to these events are not always on social media - and that’s ok! Big differences can also be made off screen. We all function in different ways. Continue to be yourself. This is meant to be mindless and something you can enjoy for a few minutes.

I’m a Heptathlete, so I’ve never run a 300m trial before. I should of kept it that way. Since sports are cancelled for the time being, I thought I’d attempt this for entertainment purposes.. (we were safe and practiced social distancing during this video). It’s 7min you can never get back!

Stay tuned for more challenges. Suggestions?

Instagram can often be curated or systematic. For the #AsSheIs campaign , I’ve decided to show some “real me” moments to bring back perspective (outside of just my sport). I encourage you to do the same! Don’t be afraid to show yourself .. as you are 😋

The ending 😂😂

Who knew I’d see the hard boiled eggs I ate this morning, twice! 
My soul died a little in today’s workout. Luckily this cold tub revived me. Almost game time 😈

node.text:
You ever realize that a few sh*tty months seem to be a precursor for all good things to eventually converge? 

In other words - it’s been a good month. But it didn’t come without a few ‘sit down in the shower’ type days 😂

node.text:
I really freaking did it!!!! I made the decision to stay in Europe after Götzis to give it my all in one more competition. I was completely alone, training for a month and then competed without a coach or any family at Ratingen. I’ve been underestimated because of my size, I’ve fallen short on multiple occasions, and I’ve even questioned myself if I’m worthy to be one of the world’s best. I had such a strong team cheering me on from home and I felt their energy throughout the entire competition. Today I said “why not me?”. 
.
.
Thank you Ratingen for putting on an incredible meet, and to the other athletes for being so welcoming. I will remember this forever ❤️

node.text:
For those of you interested, here’s some real talk about my journey so far this year ; 

I moved to Toronto when COVID hit in order to stay within my own country - we have been in lockdown for months. This means only essential services are open : no gyms, restaurants, malls, hair salons, and even our jumping pits have been closed until recently. If you travel outside of Canada, you have to quarantine in a government sanctioned hotel for 3 days (~$1500) and then continue your two weeks of isolation at home in which they constantly check on you. That means no training!
World ranking in the Heptathlon is based on both point total and bonus placement points in highly competitive meets. All competitions with bonus points are in Europe. We don’t host any competitive competitions in Canada to earn IAAF world ranking points. 

Obviously this is not the ideal situation for someone with dreams of competing for their country in Tokyo. It’s not perfect, but I will keep fighting because I love this sport and I’m thankful to have a body that is healthy and capable!! This is MY journey. I know everyone has their own - and I wish you the best in yours 😇😇😇

With that said .. OFF TO AUSTRIA NEXT WEEK FOR A HEPTATHLON!! This train don’t stop 😂😂😂
